workflow

This document discusses the typical workflow and highlights some key considerations when performing Monte Carlo simulations of financial asset markets using MCmarket.

Monte Carlo Framework

The Monte Carlo simulation routine built into MCmarket involves the following steps:

This example generates k periods of returns for D Assets across N counter-factual markets.

  1. Draw a series of k random, uniformly distributed numbers (corresponding to k trading periods), across a set of D variables (or D assets) from a multivariate Gaussian, t or Clayton copula.
    • The Gaussian and t-copulas can be specified with a correlation matrix and the Archmediean Clayton copula can be used to induce left-tail dependence. This is easily accomplished using R’s copula package [@copula].
  2. Convert the univariate distributions from uniform into something that more resembles the distribution of asset returns. For example, one could convert them into normal, student-t or skewed-generalized t distributions.
    • Practically, this is done the same way one would convert p-values into test statistics using the dnorm(), dt() and dsgt() functions respectively [@wang2012; @sgt].
    • Technically, this is accomplished via the inversion of the chosen cumulative distribution function (CDF).
  3. Induce mean and variance persistence to the series by plugging the results from step 2 into an ARMA(p,q) + GARCH(q,p) equation as the i.i.d innovations.
    • If the parameters are set accordingly, the resulting series will closely resemble real world return data.
  4. Repeat the first 3 steps N times to generate an ensemble of asset markets, each with the same risk characteristics but different realizations. ## Types of Markets

Before performing any simulations, one must first consider the type of market that they want to simulate. This involves deciding on how to set the market’s covariance matrix, choosing what multivariate distribution to use, how to set asset return distributions and their time-series properties. Since the correlation matrix is the key input when simulating markets in MCmarket, lets start by looking at some. Users can estimate their own correlation matrices with real world data, or create ad hoc matrices to simulate markets with specific dependence structures.

ad hoc/ constructed correlation matricies

  • The function gen_corr allows users to easily generate ad hoc correlation matrices with a set number of clusters and up to four layers.

corr_2 %>% ggcorrplot(title = "No Clusters")

# Correlation matrix with 5 clusters

Emperical

If the ad hoc matrices do not seem realistic enough, or the exact correlation structure is not of particular interest, then one can use empirical data to estimate a correlation matrix of their own. Alternatively, MCmarket comes with a data set of 30 correlation matrices that were each estimated from a random subset of 50 S&P500 stocks over a random time slice of 252 days between 1 January 2000 and 1 January 2020.

These correlation matrices are labeled as ‘stressed’ if they were estimated on a market where an equi-weighted basket of stocks has a Sharpe ratio below -0.5, ‘rally’ if the equi-weighted basket of stocks has a Sharpe ratio above 2 and ‘normal’ if the equi-weighted basket of stocks has a Sharpe in-between -0.5 and 2. See MCmarket::corr_mats.

Multivariate Distributions

The 2nd step in deciding what kind of market to simulate is selecting the market’s multivariate distribution. MCmarket provides functionality to select between the multivariate normal, t and Clayton copula distribution. The multivariate normal distribution has thin tails and therefore, creates relatively low risk markets, where joint drawdowns are not significantly consequential. The multivariate t distribution has a degrees of freedom parameter that can be adjusted to effect market risk. High degrees of freedom will create markets similar to that of the normal distribution, while low degrees of freedom values will produce markets with fatter tails, this can make joint drawdowns more consequential. The Clayton distribution will produce markets with left-tailed dependence, where asset correlations increase during market drawdowns. The Clayton copula also has a parameter that can be adjusted to effect the degree of left tail dependence. However, when using the Clayton copula option, the simulated markets no longer adhere to the input correlation matrix.

# Using sim_market
set.seed(123)
market_norm <-
    sim_market(
        corr_4,
        # 500 periods
        k = 500,
        mv_dist = "norm",
        # arbitrary mean and sd
        marginal_dist_model = list(mu = 0.002, sd = 0.05) 
    )

Univariate/Marginal Distributions

The next step is to decide on the the individual assets return distributions. MCmarket allows one to select between the normal, t and skewed generalized t (sgt) distributions. The sgt is the most general distribution and thereby, nests a number of alternative distributions, including the normal and t.

The first part of this step involves deciding if you want returns to be fat- or thin-tailed. If you want thin-tailed returns, then use the normal distribution or the t distribution with many degrees of freedom. If you want fat tails, then use the t-distribution with few degrees of freedom or the sgt distribution. Finally, if you want control over the skewness and/or kurtosis of the distributions, then use the sgt.

The second part involves deciding how to set the parameters of these distributions across the assets. For example, when using the normal distribution, should all assets have the same mean and sd? or should they have the same mean and different sd, or different means and sd ect.. This is up to the user and depends on the purpose of performing the Monte Carlo simulation.

The code below demonstrates how to select asset distributions using in MC_market’s sim_market functions. For simplicity, this example will use the normal distribution.

# Assigning mean = -10 and sd = 20 for all assets
m1 <- sim_market(
  corr_4,
  k = 1000,
  # selecting the pdf for the assets
  marginal_dist = "norm",
  # selecting parameters
  marginal_dist_model = list(# single arguments are assigned to all assets
    mu = -10,
    sd = 20)
)

m1 %>% group_by(Asset) %>%
    mutate(mean = mean(Return), sd = sd(Return))

Time-Series Properties

The final step is to decide on how to assign time-series properties across the assets. MCmarket has a function called sim_garch that allows users to induce time-series properties into a vector of random numbers by setting the parameters of a ARMA(1,1) + APARCH(1,1) model. The sim_market function then uses this function via is ts_model argument.

Return momentum can be induced by the ar and ma parameters, volatility persistence can be induced through the beta parameter, a leverage effect can be included through the Gamma parameter ect… The time-series parameters can be set the same across all assets or each asset’s can be set individually.

See ??MCmarket::sim_garch and ??fGarch::garchSpec for more information regarding the ARMA(1,1) + APARCH(1,1) parameters.

Note that when using the ts_model argument, the means and sd in marginal_dist_model should be left as 0 and 1, respectively. If not, then the moments are set twice and a warning message will appear.

The code below demonstrates how to use sim_garch to set the time-series properties of the simulated returns using a toy example.

set.seed(1234)
m1 <-
    sim_market(
        corr = corr_4,
        k = 500,
        mv_dist = "t",
        mv_df = 3,
        marginal_dist = "t",
        # same non centrality parameter (ncp) and df for each asset
        marginal_dist_model = list(ncp = 0, df = 20),
        # same ts_model for each asset
        ts_model = list( # Setting the same parameters for each Asset.
            # mean periodic return
            mu = 0.00002,
            # key unconditional volatility parameter
            omega = 0.00002,
            # ARCH effect
            alpha = 0.098839,
            # volatility persistence
            beta = 0.9,
            # autoregressive from ARMA
            ar = 0.063666,
            # moving average from ARMA
            ma = NULL,
            # APARCH leverage parameter
            gamma = 0.00001,
            # APARCH parameter
            delta = 1.85
        )
    )

set.seed(1234)
m2 <-
    sim_market(
        corr = corr_4,
        k = 500,
        mv_dist = "t",
        mv_df = 3,
        marginal_dist = "t",
        # same non centrality parameter (ncp) and df for each asset
        marginal_dist_model = list(ncp = 0, df = 20),
        # different ts model for each asset. at least for beta
        ts_model = list( # Setting different beta parameters for each aset.
            # mean periodic return
            mu = 0.00002,
            # key unconditional volatility parameter
            omega = 0.00002,
            # ARCH effect
            alpha = 0.098839,
            # volatility persistence
            beta = seq(0, 0.99, length.out = 50),
            # autoregressive from ARMA
            ar = 0.063666,
            # moving average from ARMA
            ma = NULL,
            # APARCH leverage parameter
            gamma = 0.00001,
            # APARCH parameter
            delta = 1.85
        )
    )

m1 %>% ggplot(aes(x = date, y = Return, color = Asset)) +
    geom_line(alpha = 0.4) + theme_bw() +
    theme(legend.position = "none") +
    labs(title = "same ts_model")

m2 %>% ggplot(aes(x = date, y = Return, color = Asset)) +
    geom_line(alpha = 0.4) + theme_bw() +
    theme(legend.position = "none") +
    labs(title = "beta 0:0.99")

Monte Carlo

Once one knows the properties of the market they wish to simulate, they can perform the Monte Carlo simulation. MCmarket provides a function called mc_market that enables users who are not comfortable using the map functions from the purrr package to perform Monte Carlo simulations using sim_market. When performing large Monte Carlo simulations, it is recommended that users iterate over sim_market by hand (see example below) as they can then use sim_market’s progress bar functionality, this is useful because calculations can take a number of minutes to complete.

The code below demonstrates how to use the mc_market function, as well as how to use purrr::map() and sim_market to perform Monte Carlo simulations with a progress bar.

# First using mc_market| Note smaller dimensions and N are used for plotting convenience
set.seed(123)
mc1 <-
  mc_market(
    corr_4,
    N = 12,
    k = 252,
    mv_dist = "norm",
    marginal_dist = "sgt",
    marginal_dist_model = list(
      mu = 0, 
      sd = 1,
      lambda = -0.05,
      p = 2,
      q = Inf
    ),
    ts_model = list(
      mu = 0.000002,
      omega = 0.00005,
      alpha = 0.7,
      beta = 0.1,
      ar = 0.05,
      ma = NULL,
      gamma = 0.05,
      delta = 1.9
    ),
    list = FALSE # for long data
  ) 

# When the output is long it is easy to plot
mc1 %>%
    group_by(Asset, Universe) %>%
    mutate(clumulative_ret = cumprod(1 + Return) * 100) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = date, y = clumulative_ret, color = Asset)) +
    geom_line() +
    facet_wrap( ~ Universe, scales = "free_y") +
    theme_bw() + 
    theme(legend.position = "none") + 
  labs(y = "Cumulative Return")

See the example of how to perform a large Monte Carlo with a progress bar.

# For large Monte Carlos map by hand with a progress bar.
pacman::p_load(MCmarket, purrr)
N <- 1000
pb <- dplyr::progress_estimated(N)   # this must be named pb

# For large N use map>map_dfr
mc2 <- map(
    1:N,
    ~ sim_market(
        corr_4,
        k = 300,
        mv_dist = "t",
        mv_df = 2.5,
        marginal_dist = "sgt",
        marginal_dist_model = list(
            mu = 0.01,
            sd = 0.1,
            # skewness parameter
            lambda = -0.2,
            # kurtosis parameter 1
            p = 2,
            # kurtosis parameter 2
            q = Inf
        ),
        progress = TRUE
    )
)
